00:32.000 --> 00:34.000
♪ ♪

00:48.000 --> 00:50.000
Beautiful.

00:50.000 --> 00:51.000
(indistinct)

00:53.000 --> 00:54.000
(indistinct chatter)

01:11.000 --> 01:13.000
How are you feeling now,
Mrs. Wellers?

01:13.000 --> 01:15.000
You’re pretty.

01:16.000 --> 01:18.000
We’re good to go.

01:36.000 --> 01:38.000
Benjamin, what are you
doing here?

01:38.000 --> 01:39.000
Who’s the woman?

01:41.000 --> 01:43.000
My girlfriend.

01:43.000 --> 01:44.000
What are you doing here?

01:44.000 --> 01:47.000
You and I...

01:49.000 --> 01:51.000
...are okay.

01:51.000 --> 01:53.000
What?

01:55.000 --> 01:57.000
Jake.

01:57.000 --> 01:59.000
Hmm?

01:59.000 --> 02:01.000
Lunch.

02:01.000 --> 02:03.000
That’s a lot
of bridesmaids.

02:04.000 --> 02:07.000
Don’t worry, I’m only
going to have eight.

02:07.000 --> 02:08.000
But it will be
in a church,

02:08.000 --> 02:10.000
and it will be big.

02:10.000 --> 02:12.000
That’s my family’s thing.

02:12.000 --> 02:14.000
Jake?

02:16.000 --> 02:17.000
I had a dream
about my brother.

02:17.000 --> 02:19.000
"Brother"?

02:19.000 --> 02:21.000
I told you
I have a brother.

02:21.000 --> 02:22.000
"I have a brother."

02:22.000 --> 02:24.000
That’s about it.

02:24.000 --> 02:26.000
He’s a rabbi.

02:26.000 --> 02:29.000
A religious one.

02:29.000 --> 02:31.000
I haven’t seen
him in six years.

02:31.000 --> 02:35.000
Now, he comes
to me in a dream.

02:35.000 --> 02:36.000
Maybe it’s time
to reconnect.

02:39.000 --> 02:41.000
Eight bridesmaids, huh?

02:41.000 --> 02:44.000
Diane, my younger
sister, had 14.

02:44.000 --> 02:46.000
Oh, that’s ridiculous.
(phone rings)

02:46.000 --> 02:48.000
Yeah, I know.

02:48.000 --> 02:50.000
Hey, Mom, what’s up?

02:53.000 --> 02:54.000
What?

02:54.000 --> 02:56.000
♪ ♪

03:11.000 --> 03:13.000
(baby cries)

03:23.000 --> 03:25.000
The brother’s
single, a doctor.

03:25.000 --> 03:27.000
He’s coming
with the mother.

03:27.000 --> 03:28.000
Point him out to me.

03:28.000 --> 03:30.000
I never met him.

03:30.000 --> 03:31.000
He’s Reform,
like the mother,

03:31.000 --> 03:33.000
who shows up once
a year, if that.

03:35.000 --> 03:37.000
Leah.

03:38.000 --> 03:40.000
You’re in
my prayers.

03:40.000 --> 03:42.000
Thank you, Mrs. Goldfarb.

03:44.000 --> 03:46.000
Malka.

03:48.000 --> 03:50.000
He should’ve
been here already.

03:50.000 --> 03:52.000
You sure you told
him the right time?

03:55.000 --> 03:58.000
Oh, I have on
open-toed shoes.

03:58.000 --> 03:59.000
What was I thinking?

03:59.000 --> 04:01.000
Ma, it’s fine.
Come on.

04:01.000 --> 04:03.000
Mama, they’re here.

04:07.000 --> 04:10.000
Dr. Lever?
Yes?

04:10.000 --> 04:12.000
My condolences to you both.

04:12.000 --> 04:14.000
If you would stand with the men.

04:14.000 --> 04:17.000
And if you would join Leah.

04:32.000 --> 04:33.000
Janice.

04:38.000 --> 04:40.000
I always thought of Benjamin
as my own son.

04:42.000 --> 04:43.000
Here, sit.

04:48.000 --> 04:50.000
In the days
and weeks to come,

04:50.000 --> 04:53.000
when we think Rabbi Lever,

04:53.000 --> 04:55.000
we may be compelled
to ask God,

04:55.000 --> 04:57.000
"Why?

04:57.000 --> 04:59.000
"Why would a man
so full of life,

04:59.000 --> 05:02.000
"in his prime

05:02.000 --> 05:05.000
be taken from his wife
and his family?"

05:05.000 --> 05:09.000
We come into this world
with a purpose.

05:09.000 --> 05:13.000
And because death
is so much a part of life...

05:15.000 --> 05:18.000
...we come to see
Benjamin’s departure,

05:18.000 --> 05:20.000
as a, a lesson,

05:20.000 --> 05:23.000
which we must take as a gift.

05:23.000 --> 05:25.000
And in time,

05:25.000 --> 05:28.000
it will become apparent

05:28.000 --> 05:30.000
what his gift is

05:30.000 --> 05:32.000
to each of us.

05:34.000 --> 05:36.000
Amen.
MEN:
Amen.

05:48.000 --> 05:50.000
(whispers):
Are they going to stare at us
the whole time?

05:50.000 --> 05:51.000
Shh-shh, shh-shh.

05:51.000 --> 05:52.000
Danish?

05:52.000 --> 05:54.000
No, thank you.
No, thank you.

05:54.000 --> 05:56.000
I’ll be back around
with a tray of fruit.

05:56.000 --> 05:58.000
I think the fruit
comes next.

05:59.000 --> 06:01.000
Esther.

06:01.000 --> 06:04.000
Why he never comes to visit?

06:04.000 --> 06:05.000
He disapproves of us?

06:05.000 --> 06:06.000
MALKA:
Esther!

06:08.000 --> 06:10.000
The fruit is ready.

06:12.000 --> 06:14.000
To drop dead
just like that--

06:14.000 --> 06:16.000
I tell you, it’s best
that Leah has no children.

06:16.000 --> 06:18.000
It’s a terrible thing

06:18.000 --> 06:20.000
when children
are left...
Yeah, I know.

06:20.000 --> 06:22.000
Well, what happens now?
Well, Rabbi Tenzer’s

06:22.000 --> 06:25.000
family will take the apartment
since the shul owns it,

06:25.000 --> 06:26.000
and Leah’ll move
back here with me.

06:26.000 --> 06:29.000
Oh...

06:29.000 --> 06:30.000
Janice?

06:30.000 --> 06:32.000
Can I get you something?

06:32.000 --> 06:34.000
Nothing, thank you.

06:34.000 --> 06:36.000
I’m going to get some air.

07:01.000 --> 07:03.000
Sorry, look, I’ll...

07:03.000 --> 07:05.000
It’s okay.

07:05.000 --> 07:07.000
I should go.

07:07.000 --> 07:09.000
Don’t leave

07:09.000 --> 07:10.000
because of me.

07:10.000 --> 07:12.000
I should be downstairs.

07:12.000 --> 07:13.000
I just needed some air.

07:18.000 --> 07:19.000
I wish I had worn an old suit.

07:22.000 --> 07:24.000
What’s the meaning behind it?

07:24.000 --> 07:26.000
The rending of the garments.

07:28.000 --> 07:30.000
It allows the mourners
to express

07:30.000 --> 07:31.000
their grief and anger.

07:33.000 --> 07:36.000
There are things of Benjamin’s
you should have.

07:36.000 --> 07:40.000
Thanks, but don’t rush.

07:40.000 --> 07:42.000
I know you have to pack.

07:42.000 --> 07:43.000
I heard you’re moving.

07:43.000 --> 07:45.000
It’s just down two flights.

07:45.000 --> 07:47.000
Your mother lives
in the same building?

07:47.000 --> 07:49.000
Yes, and my sister, too.

07:55.000 --> 07:57.000
He wanted you in his life.

07:57.000 --> 07:58.000
I know he did.

07:58.000 --> 08:01.000
I just couldn’t find a way
to relate to him.

08:03.000 --> 08:05.000
Everything I did was sinful.

08:10.000 --> 08:12.000
I should have been around.

08:12.000 --> 08:13.000
You know, I might,
I might have

08:13.000 --> 08:15.000
seen the signs, and then...

08:15.000 --> 08:18.000
you and I, you and I wouldn’t
be standing here right now.

08:23.000 --> 08:24.000
When it happened,

08:24.000 --> 08:27.000
Benjamin couldn’t find me.

08:27.000 --> 08:29.000
I should have felt something
when he died.

08:32.000 --> 08:34.000
He couldn’t find me
to say good-bye.

08:34.000 --> 08:36.000
What do you mean?

08:36.000 --> 08:39.000
A person’s soul finds the one
they love to say good-bye.

08:49.000 --> 08:52.000
He found you?

08:55.000 --> 08:56.000
It was just a dream.

08:56.000 --> 08:57.000
(door opens)

08:57.000 --> 08:59.000
The rabbi is downstairs.

08:59.000 --> 09:00.000
You’re wanted now.

09:00.000 --> 09:02.000
Oh, you, too.

09:02.000 --> 09:04.000
Me?

09:04.000 --> 09:06.000
(clears throat)

09:06.000 --> 09:08.000
The Levirate Marriage
takes place

09:08.000 --> 09:11.000
between the childless widow
whose husband

09:11.000 --> 09:13.000
has just died
and the unmarried

09:13.000 --> 09:14.000
brother of
the deceased.

09:14.000 --> 09:17.000
It’s his obligation
to marry her,

09:17.000 --> 09:20.000
so the brother’s name
will carry on.

09:21.000 --> 09:22.000
You’re kidding right?

09:30.000 --> 09:33.000
Well, I-I, I can’t.

09:33.000 --> 09:34.000
I’m in a relationship.
I’m sorry, but...

09:36.000 --> 09:37.000
I mean,
it’s no offense, Leah,

09:37.000 --> 09:39.000
or to all of you, but I...

09:39.000 --> 09:41.000
Shh-shh, Dr. Lever.

09:41.000 --> 09:42.000
We no longer practice this.

09:42.000 --> 09:44.000
However,
to release

09:44.000 --> 09:46.000
both of you from
your obligation,

09:46.000 --> 09:47.000
we have to perform a ceremony.

09:47.000 --> 09:49.000
Great. What do I have to do?

09:49.000 --> 09:50.000
You have to wait
three months

09:50.000 --> 09:52.000
to see if Leah is pregnant.

09:52.000 --> 09:55.000
If not, we reconvene

09:55.000 --> 09:56.000
for the Halizah,

09:56.000 --> 09:58.000
that’s the
ceremony that will

09:58.000 --> 09:59.000
release Leah from the law.

10:23.000 --> 10:24.000
(door unlocking)

10:24.000 --> 10:26.000
Tante.

10:26.000 --> 10:29.000
All right,
everybody inside.

10:29.000 --> 10:30.000
No running like meshugges, huh?

10:30.000 --> 10:33.000
Come on, come on,
in you go.

10:33.000 --> 10:34.000
In you go.

10:34.000 --> 10:36.000
Hannah Rifka?

10:36.000 --> 10:39.000
Come. You’re in charge, okay?

10:39.000 --> 10:40.000
Play quietly.

10:42.000 --> 10:43.000
Bubbe, she has
more toys!

10:43.000 --> 10:45.000
What a mistake
giving them sugar.

10:45.000 --> 10:47.000
Here, I saved the last
two doughnuts for us.

10:50.000 --> 10:51.000
Have you seen Mama yet?

10:51.000 --> 10:54.000
Why?

10:54.000 --> 10:55.000
She’s meeting
with Mrs. Finkelman.

10:55.000 --> 10:56.000
(sighs)

10:57.000 --> 11:01.000
I’m sure it’s only
preliminary, you know?

11:01.000 --> 11:05.000
To see who’s out there
and interested in you.

11:05.000 --> 11:07.000
Nothing can really happen
if you’re...

11:07.000 --> 11:09.000
What? Pregnant?

11:09.000 --> 11:12.000
I’m not pregnant,
and you and Mama know it.

11:12.000 --> 11:13.000
Things do happen.

11:20.000 --> 11:22.000
She called the matchmaker?

11:24.000 --> 11:26.000
What is her hurry?

11:33.000 --> 11:35.000
I got other plans, Essy.

11:36.000 --> 11:38.000
I don’t like that look.

11:44.000 --> 11:46.000
What are you digging?

11:59.000 --> 12:00.000
Vayzmeer.

12:00.000 --> 12:03.000
I’ve got my interview
this afternoon.

12:03.000 --> 12:06.000
How are you going
to tell Mama?

12:06.000 --> 12:08.000
Winging this
would not be advised.

12:08.000 --> 12:10.000
I’m not moving
back in with Mama.

12:10.000 --> 12:11.000
Come on,
I’m going to be late.

12:11.000 --> 12:13.000
Help me with my wig.

12:13.000 --> 12:15.000
♪ ♪

12:37.000 --> 12:38.000
We’ve got your
transcripts.

12:38.000 --> 12:40.000
You’re not applying
for financial aid.

12:40.000 --> 12:41.000
You plan to matriculate

12:41.000 --> 12:43.000
as a bachelor’s
candidate.

12:43.000 --> 12:44.000
That’s right.

12:44.000 --> 12:46.000
So, uh, okay,

12:46.000 --> 12:48.000
well, all we need are
your, uh, SAT scores.

12:50.000 --> 12:53.000
Yeah, uh, no, I know
I have to get that over with.

12:53.000 --> 12:55.000
So are you applying

12:55.000 --> 12:56.000
for housing?
Oh, yes.

12:56.000 --> 12:58.000
Actually...

12:58.000 --> 13:01.000
do you have a kosher meal plan?

13:01.000 --> 13:03.000
We do-- I’ll, uh, I’ll
make a note of it.

13:03.000 --> 13:05.000
So you’ll be requesting
a roommate who is also

13:05.000 --> 13:08.000
of your faith?
Oh. I didn’t even know
that was an option

13:08.000 --> 13:11.000
seeing I’m applying so late
for this semester.

13:11.000 --> 13:12.000
Oh, Mrs. Lever,

13:12.000 --> 13:15.000
the earliest if accepted
here or... anywhere

13:15.000 --> 13:17.000
would-would be
for next semester.

13:17.000 --> 13:20.000
That’s almost six months away.

13:20.000 --> 13:22.000
Yeah, I know.
I’m sorry.

13:24.000 --> 13:26.000
You’re covering for me
in clinic tomorrow, right?

13:26.000 --> 13:29.000
Sure. What’s up?

13:29.000 --> 13:31.000
Remember? I have to be in
Brooklyn tomorrow morning

13:31.000 --> 13:33.000
to divorce my sister-in-law.

13:33.000 --> 13:36.000
Right. And people think
my religion’s strange.

13:36.000 --> 13:38.000
What do you have to do?

13:38.000 --> 13:39.000
It’s all online.

13:39.000 --> 13:43.000
Recite some biblical passages,
get spit on by Leah,

13:43.000 --> 13:46.000
and then the rabbi will
consider my obligation broken.

13:46.000 --> 13:48.000
Strictly ceremonial.

13:48.000 --> 13:49.000
No. It’s my experience

13:49.000 --> 13:52.000
that in the presence
of God and religious men

13:52.000 --> 13:53.000
that nothing’s
strictly ceremonial,

13:53.000 --> 13:55.000
especially when
there’s spitting.

13:55.000 --> 13:58.000
Oh. That, they say,
signifies...

13:58.000 --> 14:01.000
Oh, one special.

14:01.000 --> 14:03.000
Ten even, please.

14:03.000 --> 14:04.000
"To shame the brother

14:04.000 --> 14:07.000
for not building up
his brother’s house."

14:07.000 --> 14:09.000
"For he shall
be forgotten now

14:09.000 --> 14:13.000
that no offspring shall
be raised in his name."

14:14.000 --> 14:17.000
It sounds different
when it’s read aloud.

14:17.000 --> 14:19.000
Like I said.

14:19.000 --> 14:21.000
WOMAN (on screen):
Do you love him, Loretta?

14:21.000 --> 14:24.000
Ma, I love him awful.
Oh, God, that’s too bad.

14:26.000 --> 14:29.000
MAN:
She loves me.

14:29.000 --> 14:32.000
♪ ♪

14:33.000 --> 14:35.000
What’s the
matter, Pop?

14:35.000 --> 14:37.000
(crying) I’m confused.

14:37.000 --> 14:40.000
(champagne cork pops)

14:40.000 --> 14:42.000
(several characters
speaking at once)

14:47.000 --> 14:49.000
♪ ♪

15:02.000 --> 15:03.000
(doorbell jingles)

15:03.000 --> 15:05.000
I’m sorry I’m late, Ruth.

15:05.000 --> 15:07.000
You have Mama’s order ready?

15:07.000 --> 15:08.000
Yeah.

15:08.000 --> 15:10.000
♪ ♪

15:23.000 --> 15:25.000
LEAH:
Hi, Mama. Ruth gave away
your lemon cake,

15:25.000 --> 15:27.000
so...
MAMA:
Oh...

15:27.000 --> 15:28.000
here she is.

15:28.000 --> 15:30.000
I told Carmie you
might stop by.

15:30.000 --> 15:32.000
Join us for a
L’Chaim, Leah.

15:32.000 --> 15:34.000
Mrs. Finkelman
thought it’d be nice

15:34.000 --> 15:36.000
for you two to
get reacquainted.

15:36.000 --> 15:37.000
Hello, Leah.

15:38.000 --> 15:40.000
Hi, Carmie.

15:42.000 --> 15:44.000
♪ ♪

15:55.000 --> 15:57.000
♪ ♪

16:00.000 --> 16:04.000
Why do you have to go
so far away, Benjie?

16:04.000 --> 16:06.000
There are good
colleges right here.

16:06.000 --> 16:08.000
I just do.

16:11.000 --> 16:13.000
I want you to
have something.

16:20.000 --> 16:22.000
This a Jewish thing?

16:22.000 --> 16:26.000
It’s a Hamsa,
for each of us.

16:26.000 --> 16:27.000
It protects against
evil forces.

16:29.000 --> 16:32.000
Bless these artifacts
and make them holy.

16:32.000 --> 16:34.000
Let them be a symbol
of our bond.

16:34.000 --> 16:36.000
We will always be
there for each other,

16:36.000 --> 16:37.000
no matter what.

16:37.000 --> 16:39.000
No matter what.

16:39.000 --> 16:41.000
Amen.

16:41.000 --> 16:44.000
♪ ♪

16:47.000 --> 16:49.000
(doorbell buzzes)

16:56.000 --> 16:58.000
Hey.
Hey.

16:58.000 --> 17:00.000
I’m right
over here.

17:00.000 --> 17:02.000
When does your
train leave?

17:02.000 --> 17:05.000
Not for another hour.

17:05.000 --> 17:07.000
What is that?

17:07.000 --> 17:09.000
My brother’s prayer shawl.

17:09.000 --> 17:12.000
Leah’s note said Ben wore
this one on the High Holidays.

17:12.000 --> 17:17.000
Really? Do you have to
wear it for the ceremony?

17:17.000 --> 17:18.000
I don’t know.

17:18.000 --> 17:21.000
"Be prepared" is my motto.

17:21.000 --> 17:23.000
I’ll definitely be needing
one of these, however.

17:23.000 --> 17:25.000
(laughs)

17:28.000 --> 17:30.000
So, is Leah nice?

17:30.000 --> 17:32.000
Is she pretty?

17:32.000 --> 17:34.000
She’s pretty religious.

17:34.000 --> 17:37.000
She can still be pretty.

17:37.000 --> 17:40.000
Do you think you’ll keep in
touch with her after this?

17:40.000 --> 17:42.000
I hadn’t really
thought about it.

17:42.000 --> 17:44.000
It’s not like we
have much in common.

17:44.000 --> 17:47.000
Except your brother.

17:47.000 --> 17:49.000
Make an effort, Jake.

17:49.000 --> 17:51.000
She’s family.

17:54.000 --> 17:57.000
♪ ♪

18:09.000 --> 18:11.000
MAMA (calls):
Leah?

18:17.000 --> 18:19.000
(footsteps approaching)
Leah?

18:19.000 --> 18:22.000
Leah.

18:22.000 --> 18:24.000
The new tenants are ready
to hang the drapes.

18:24.000 --> 18:25.000
You’re still going
through boxes?

18:27.000 --> 18:30.000
I’m going away to college.

18:33.000 --> 18:35.000
Okay.

18:35.000 --> 18:37.000
I’ve got this figured out, Mama.

18:37.000 --> 18:38.000
I’m sure you
think you do.

18:39.000 --> 18:41.000
Tell me.

18:41.000 --> 18:44.000
Does running off to college
include a family, huh?

18:44.000 --> 18:46.000
I’m not any good at marriage.

18:47.000 --> 18:50.000
All right,
this is grief talking.

18:50.000 --> 18:51.000
Mama...
No, it is.

18:53.000 --> 18:56.000
You were a good wife
to Benjamin, Leah.

18:56.000 --> 18:58.000
What do you think,
every marriage

18:58.000 --> 19:00.000
doesn’t have its
share of problems?

19:00.000 --> 19:02.000
He loved you, Leah.
I know, Mama.

19:02.000 --> 19:04.000
I just always...

19:07.000 --> 19:10.000
...thought that...

19:10.000 --> 19:14.000
a marriage could be
something more.

19:14.000 --> 19:18.000
You’re living
in a fantasy world.

19:18.000 --> 19:21.000
Marriage is not
like those movies

19:21.000 --> 19:22.000
you’re always
sneaking off to see.

19:24.000 --> 19:29.000
Before I married your father,
I lived in that world.

19:29.000 --> 19:32.000
Everybody chasing
crazy dreams...

19:32.000 --> 19:35.000
looking outward
inside of inside themselves

19:35.000 --> 19:38.000
for a spiritual life.

19:38.000 --> 19:41.000
Leah...

19:41.000 --> 19:45.000
the answers you seek are not
to be found in a movie theater

19:45.000 --> 19:46.000
or a college campus.

19:48.000 --> 19:51.000
Well, maybe for you
they weren’t, Mama.

19:52.000 --> 19:53.000
Leah...

19:53.000 --> 19:56.000
you have got to erase

19:56.000 --> 19:59.000
this meshugge dream
from your head.

20:00.000 --> 20:02.000
I can’t.

20:04.000 --> 20:05.000
Then I fear

20:05.000 --> 20:08.000
God may grant it to you.

20:11.000 --> 20:14.000
After you put on
the Halizah shoe,
take a walk in it.

20:14.000 --> 20:15.000
Make sure it fits.

20:18.000 --> 20:20.000
Walk here, in front
of the judges.

20:31.000 --> 20:33.000
It fits.

20:33.000 --> 20:35.000
Okay.

20:35.000 --> 20:36.000
Now, Leah,
repeat after me.

20:36.000 --> 20:40.000
"My husband’s brother
refuses to establish a name

20:40.000 --> 20:42.000
for his brother
within Israel."

20:42.000 --> 20:45.000
My husband’s brother refuses
to establish a name

20:45.000 --> 20:47.000
for his brother
within Israel.

20:47.000 --> 20:48.000
"He does
not consent

20:48.000 --> 20:51.000
to perform
the Levirate marriage to me."

20:51.000 --> 20:55.000
He does not consent to perform
the Levirate marriage to me.

20:55.000 --> 20:57.000
Do you prefer
to marry your sister-in-law

20:57.000 --> 20:58.000
or release her through
this ceremony?

20:58.000 --> 20:59.000
Release her.

20:59.000 --> 21:02.000
All right, go lean
against the wall over there.

21:06.000 --> 21:08.000
Now press your foot down
hard hard on the ground.

21:08.000 --> 21:10.000
All right, now, Leah,

21:10.000 --> 21:12.000
go over and put your
left hand on Jacob’s calf.

21:14.000 --> 21:15.000
Go on, it’s all right.

21:15.000 --> 21:16.000
Go on.

21:20.000 --> 21:22.000
Then with your
right hand,

21:22.000 --> 21:23.000
undo the loops

21:23.000 --> 21:25.000
on the Halizah shoe.

21:39.000 --> 21:41.000
Now raise his leg.

21:43.000 --> 21:45.000
No, not so high.

21:46.000 --> 21:48.000
Now, take off the
shoe and cast it

21:48.000 --> 21:49.000
across the room.

21:57.000 --> 21:59.000
Put down his leg.
Now, Leah...

21:59.000 --> 22:00.000
spit on the floor
in front of Jacob.

22:05.000 --> 22:06.000
(spits)
Now, repeat
after me, Leah.

22:06.000 --> 22:09.000
"That is what shall
be done unto the man

22:09.000 --> 22:11.000
who doth not build up
his brother’s house."

22:11.000 --> 22:12.000
LEAH:
This is what
shall be done

22:12.000 --> 22:16.000
to the man that doth not
build up his brother’s house.

22:16.000 --> 22:18.000
JUDGE:
Jacob, you deny
your brother’s existence?

22:19.000 --> 22:22.000
You deny

22:22.000 --> 22:23.000
your brother’s
existence?

22:29.000 --> 22:30.000
(whispers):
We got to talk.

22:30.000 --> 22:33.000
RABBI:
Dr. Lever?
We’ll be right back, Rabbi.

22:36.000 --> 22:38.000
I can’t do this, Leah.

22:38.000 --> 22:40.000
I thought I could,

22:40.000 --> 22:41.000
but I can’t.

22:41.000 --> 22:42.000
You have to, Jake.

22:42.000 --> 22:45.000
Because if you
don’t, then...

22:45.000 --> 22:47.000
you will be obligated
to marry me.

22:47.000 --> 22:49.000
Then I’ll marry you.

22:49.000 --> 22:51.000
I can’t go back
in there and let them
finish this ceremony.

22:51.000 --> 22:54.000
If I do, I’ll be denying
my brother’s existence.

22:54.000 --> 22:57.000
I did that, for years,

22:57.000 --> 23:00.000
and now he’s gone,
and I... I j...

23:00.000 --> 23:01.000
I can’t.

23:04.000 --> 23:06.000
(sighs)

23:06.000 --> 23:08.000
I worshipped him.

23:13.000 --> 23:16.000
He gave me one, too.

23:16.000 --> 23:18.000
I kept it with me...

23:20.000 --> 23:22.000
...since I was 11.

23:22.000 --> 23:24.000
We can do this.

23:24.000 --> 23:27.000
Not like what you
and Ben had, but...

23:27.000 --> 23:30.000
Uh, what are you
suggesting?

23:30.000 --> 23:32.000
We’ll be roommates;
separate bedrooms.

23:32.000 --> 23:36.000
Didn’t you say you
have a girlfriend?
Yes.

23:36.000 --> 23:38.000
But she’ll understand;
family’s very important to her.

23:43.000 --> 23:45.000
My plan is to
go to college--

23:45.000 --> 23:48.000
is that gonna be
a problem for you?

23:48.000 --> 23:49.000
Not at all.

23:49.000 --> 23:52.000
There’s plenty of
good colleges in DC.

23:52.000 --> 23:55.000
My mother would have to
believe that we are married

23:55.000 --> 23:58.000
in the traditional way--
if we do this.

23:58.000 --> 23:59.000
Absolutely.

23:59.000 --> 24:02.000
But, then...
really, we would...

24:02.000 --> 24:04.000
have separate lives.

24:04.000 --> 24:06.000
Is that what you mean?

24:06.000 --> 24:08.000
Yes. Yes.

24:11.000 --> 24:12.000
(clears throat)

24:12.000 --> 24:14.000
All right.

24:14.000 --> 24:16.000
We’ll start, uh,

24:16.000 --> 24:18.000
begin at, uh...
JAKE:
We’d...
actually like

24:18.000 --> 24:20.000
to talk about
the other ceremony.

24:20.000 --> 24:21.000
What other ceremony?

24:22.000 --> 24:24.000
Marriage.

24:33.000 --> 24:34.000
(horn honks)

24:36.000 --> 24:38.000
(sighs) I know Jake
wasn’t your choice,

24:38.000 --> 24:42.000
or Mrs. Finkelman’s,
but I did as you wanted.

24:44.000 --> 24:46.000
Maybe this is God’s plan.

24:46.000 --> 24:48.000
Only He commands

24:48.000 --> 24:50.000
who shall be
with whom,

24:50.000 --> 24:51.000
Mama.

24:56.000 --> 24:58.000
(sighs)

24:58.000 --> 25:01.000
It’s gonna be fine. Really.

25:01.000 --> 25:03.000
He’s not religious.

25:03.000 --> 25:05.000
And this is far from fine.

25:18.000 --> 25:21.000
♪ ♪

25:21.000 --> 25:24.000
No, I got it, I got it.

25:24.000 --> 25:25.000
Thank you.

25:27.000 --> 25:29.000
So, who lives there?

25:30.000 --> 25:32.000
Are you serious?

25:32.000 --> 25:34.000
(laughs) No.

25:34.000 --> 25:35.000
It’s a joke.

25:35.000 --> 25:37.000
(laughs)

25:40.000 --> 25:42.000
This is your home?
Yeah.

25:42.000 --> 25:45.000
Oh, but... only
the first floor.

25:59.000 --> 26:01.000
JAKE:
Sorry, I...

26:01.000 --> 26:03.000
wasn’t expecting company.

26:03.000 --> 26:05.000
Or a wife.

26:05.000 --> 26:06.000
(chuckles) Yeah, right.

26:06.000 --> 26:08.000
It’s nice.

26:08.000 --> 26:11.000
Well, it’s, uh, usually cleaner.

26:11.000 --> 26:13.000
At least... tidier.

26:13.000 --> 26:17.000
But don’t worry, I have someone
who comes in and cleans

26:17.000 --> 26:18.000
once a week, so...
I can’t believe

26:18.000 --> 26:20.000
I’m going to be living
in Washington, DC.

26:20.000 --> 26:23.000
It’s actually Georgetown.

26:25.000 --> 26:27.000
It’s not my mother’s house.
Come on,

26:27.000 --> 26:29.000
I’ll show you your room.

26:29.000 --> 26:32.000
It’s, uh, kind of
a mess right now, but...

26:32.000 --> 26:35.000
don’t worry, I’m gonna...
I’m gonna clear it out for you.

26:35.000 --> 26:36.000
There’s a storage area in back.

26:36.000 --> 26:38.000
♪ ♪

26:44.000 --> 26:46.000
This’ll be just fine.

26:46.000 --> 26:49.000
Great. Well, um, I’m gonna
make some room for you

26:49.000 --> 26:51.000
in the medicine cabinet--
how many shelves do you need?

26:51.000 --> 26:53.000
One.

27:02.000 --> 27:04.000
You must be hungry.

27:08.000 --> 27:11.000
Here. One of these
is probably kosher.

27:11.000 --> 27:12.000
No. I’ll shop tomorrow.

27:12.000 --> 27:14.000
What do you want
me to buy you?

27:14.000 --> 27:16.000
Oh, no, don’t worry about me.

27:16.000 --> 27:17.000
You just take care of you.

27:17.000 --> 27:20.000
Map. You’re gonna need a map.

27:20.000 --> 27:22.000
(drawer rattling)

27:25.000 --> 27:28.000
(grunts)
I fight my junk drawer
just like the Maccabees.

27:28.000 --> 27:29.000
(both laugh)

27:29.000 --> 27:31.000
Maccabees, right.

27:31.000 --> 27:34.000
Um, I know you know
that I’m not religious,

27:34.000 --> 27:37.000
but I’m-I’m
really not religious.

27:37.000 --> 27:39.000
How you choose to live

27:39.000 --> 27:41.000
is between you and Him.

27:43.000 --> 27:46.000
(drawer rattling)

27:49.000 --> 27:51.000
(grunts)

27:51.000 --> 27:52.000
All right.

27:57.000 --> 27:59.000
Map. House key.

27:59.000 --> 28:01.000
You know,

28:01.000 --> 28:04.000
I just don’t... I don’t want
my lifestyle to offend you.

28:04.000 --> 28:06.000
I’m in the middle
of my fellowship,

28:06.000 --> 28:09.000
and I work long, odd hours,
I’m not here that much, and...

28:09.000 --> 28:11.000
when I am, I’m
usually sleeping.

28:11.000 --> 28:13.000
But you’ll be
in school--

28:13.000 --> 28:15.000
you said you wanted
to go to college, right?

28:15.000 --> 28:16.000
Yeah.

28:18.000 --> 28:19.000
Do you think...

28:19.000 --> 28:22.000
that at my age, that’s...

28:22.000 --> 28:24.000
a crazy dream?

28:24.000 --> 28:26.000
No, no. My first
year of med school,

28:26.000 --> 28:28.000
my roommate was 35.

28:28.000 --> 28:29.000
(beeping)

28:33.000 --> 28:34.000
(chuckles softly)

28:34.000 --> 28:36.000
Like I said, I’m never here.

28:37.000 --> 28:40.000
(calling):
I could, uh,
drop you off somewhere

28:40.000 --> 28:43.000
on my way to the hospital--
you could check out M Street.

28:43.000 --> 28:46.000
No, I think I’ll
stay and unpack.

28:46.000 --> 28:47.000
Hey, do you need
any money?

28:47.000 --> 28:49.000
(quiet gasp)

28:49.000 --> 28:51.000
No, thank you.

28:57.000 --> 28:58.000
All my numbers.

29:02.000 --> 29:03.000
So, I’ll, uh...

29:03.000 --> 29:05.000
I’ll see you.

29:05.000 --> 29:07.000
See you.

29:07.000 --> 29:08.000
Yeah.

29:10.000 --> 29:13.000
See you when?

29:13.000 --> 29:14.000
Um...

29:14.000 --> 29:16.000
I’m not sure.

29:16.000 --> 29:17.000
But soon.

29:17.000 --> 29:19.000
Tomorrow morning, maybe.

29:21.000 --> 29:24.000
Will you do me a favor

29:24.000 --> 29:25.000
and just let
the machine

29:25.000 --> 29:27.000
pick up if anyone calls.

29:27.000 --> 29:29.000
I should first tell people
what’s going on here.

29:29.000 --> 29:32.000
It is probably best
to do in person.

29:32.000 --> 29:33.000
(chuckles)

29:33.000 --> 29:36.000
Yeah.

29:36.000 --> 29:38.000
All right, um...

29:38.000 --> 29:40.000
I’ll see you.

29:44.000 --> 29:47.000
(door closes)

29:47.000 --> 29:48.000
You married her?!

29:48.000 --> 29:51.000
Yes, but not in
the biblical way.

29:51.000 --> 29:53.000
We’re roommates-- she’ll have
her life; I’ll have mine.

29:53.000 --> 29:55.000
There’s nothing
more to it.
You were supposed

29:55.000 --> 29:57.000
to go there and get unmarried,

29:57.000 --> 29:58.000
not bring her back
as your bride!

29:58.000 --> 30:01.000
I know, but I
couldn’t do it.

30:01.000 --> 30:04.000
I just couldn’t.

30:04.000 --> 30:06.000
You did say I should
stay in touch with her--

30:06.000 --> 30:08.000
that was your idea.
Shut up. Shut up.

30:08.000 --> 30:10.000
14 months we’ve
been going together.

30:10.000 --> 30:12.000
I’m the one that you
should be getting married to.

30:12.000 --> 30:14.000
You said you wanted
to take it slow.

30:14.000 --> 30:16.000
I know what I said,
but I didn’t think

30:16.000 --> 30:17.000
you were gonna marry
somebody else first!

30:17.000 --> 30:19.000
We’re roommates.
Roommates.

30:19.000 --> 30:20.000
You call it "roommates"--

30:20.000 --> 30:23.000
everyone here
will call it married.

30:23.000 --> 30:24.000
How old is she?
You know, it doesn’t matter.

30:24.000 --> 30:25.000
You’re married. That’s it.

30:25.000 --> 30:27.000
You’re not hearing me.

30:27.000 --> 30:28.000
No, you’re not hearing me.

30:28.000 --> 30:31.000
Until you get unmarried,
we’re done!

30:33.000 --> 30:35.000
(chuckles)
Oh, come...

30:35.000 --> 30:37.000
(door opens)
Carol...

30:45.000 --> 30:48.000
Good morning.

30:48.000 --> 30:49.000
Do you like scrambled eggs?

30:57.000 --> 30:59.000
Do you want a cup of tea?

30:59.000 --> 31:01.000
Uh, coffee’s fine, thanks.

31:04.000 --> 31:06.000
(pouring coffee)

31:06.000 --> 31:08.000
I made you lunch.

31:08.000 --> 31:11.000
(chuckles) You really
don’t have to wait on me,

31:11.000 --> 31:12.000
cook for me.

31:14.000 --> 31:17.000
Some habits are hard
to break, I guess.

31:17.000 --> 31:18.000
Right.
Can I now

31:18.000 --> 31:20.000
pick up the phone if it rings?

31:20.000 --> 31:21.000
Sure.

31:21.000 --> 31:25.000
So Carol is fine
with me being here?

31:25.000 --> 31:26.000
She’s very cool with it, yeah.

31:28.000 --> 31:30.000
I really should run.

31:47.000 --> 31:48.000
Mmm.

31:48.000 --> 31:51.000
These are really good.

31:53.000 --> 31:55.000
By the way,
a man is coming today

31:55.000 --> 31:57.000
to blow-torch your oven.

31:59.000 --> 32:00.000
Makes it kosher.

32:00.000 --> 32:03.000
Okay.

32:03.000 --> 32:05.000
Well, I got to go.

32:06.000 --> 32:08.000
Oh, don’t forget
your lunch.

32:10.000 --> 32:11.000
(chuckles)

32:11.000 --> 32:12.000
Thanks.

32:18.000 --> 32:21.000
(gentle intro playing)

32:21.000 --> 32:22.000
♪ Long walks ♪

32:22.000 --> 32:24.000
♪ In the dark ♪

32:24.000 --> 32:27.000
♪ Through woods grown
behind the park ♪

32:27.000 --> 32:29.000
♪ I asked God ♪

32:29.000 --> 32:32.000
♪ Who I’m supposed to be ♪

32:34.000 --> 32:37.000
♪ The stars smile down on me ♪

32:37.000 --> 32:38.000
♪ God answered ♪

32:38.000 --> 32:40.000
♪ In silent reverie ♪

32:40.000 --> 32:42.000
♪ I said a prayer ♪

32:42.000 --> 32:44.000
♪ And fell asleep ♪

32:46.000 --> 32:48.000
♪ I had a dream ♪

32:50.000 --> 32:52.000
♪ I could fly ♪

32:52.000 --> 32:56.000
♪ From the highest tree ♪

32:56.000 --> 32:58.000
♪ I had a dream ♪

33:00.000 --> 33:02.000
♪ Ooh ♪

33:02.000 --> 33:05.000
♪ Ooh, ooh, ooh... ♪

33:06.000 --> 33:07.000
Welcome, movers and shakers

33:07.000 --> 33:09.000
of tomorrow.

33:09.000 --> 33:11.000
So, you are here
to prepare for the SAT,

33:11.000 --> 33:14.000
the mother of all tests.

33:14.000 --> 33:16.000
You can say good-bye to your,

33:16.000 --> 33:19.000
uh, TV, your iPod, your...

33:19.000 --> 33:20.000
text-messaging

33:20.000 --> 33:21.000
for the next eight weeks.

33:21.000 --> 33:23.000
On your desks,

33:23.000 --> 33:24.000
you will find a packet

33:24.000 --> 33:26.000
that contains your
study material.

33:26.000 --> 33:27.000
Please take those out,

33:27.000 --> 33:29.000
and let’s begin.

33:29.000 --> 33:32.000
JAKE:
Can I see this one, please?

33:32.000 --> 33:33.000
Not gold, dude.

33:33.000 --> 33:35.000
What you did
calls for platinum.

33:35.000 --> 33:36.000
I have it in platinum.

33:36.000 --> 33:37.000
One moment.

33:38.000 --> 33:40.000
Welcome to matrimony.

33:40.000 --> 33:41.000
I’m not married.

33:41.000 --> 33:43.000
Not like you and Priya
are married.

33:43.000 --> 33:45.000
Eventually, Leah will move out,
we’ll get this annulled.

33:45.000 --> 33:47.000
You mean divorced.
Whatever.
Leah will move on,

33:47.000 --> 33:49.000
Carol will calm down,
and everything will go back

33:49.000 --> 33:51.000
to the way it was.
And you’re on Demerol.

33:51.000 --> 33:53.000
Here it is.

33:54.000 --> 33:56.000
The other one
didn’t have diamonds.

33:56.000 --> 33:57.000
I know.

33:57.000 --> 33:59.000
We’re out of
those-- but...

33:59.000 --> 34:02.000
these are Pavé diamonds.

34:02.000 --> 34:03.000
She’ll love them.

34:06.000 --> 34:07.000
How much?

34:07.000 --> 34:09.000
Only $4,200.

34:09.000 --> 34:10.000
(chuckles)
He’ll take it.

34:13.000 --> 34:17.000
(woman singing in distance,
vacuum running)

34:17.000 --> 34:22.000
♪ Yeah, yeah, yeah, yeah,
oh, yeah, yeah, yeah ♪

34:22.000 --> 34:24.000
♪ Uh-huh, huh ♪

34:24.000 --> 34:26.000
♪ All right,
all right, now ♪

34:26.000 --> 34:28.000
♪ Hey, hey, hey, hey ♪

34:28.000 --> 34:29.000
♪ Hey, yeah ♪

34:29.000 --> 34:31.000
♪ Uh, uh, uh ♪

34:31.000 --> 34:33.000
♪ Uh-huh, uh-huh,
uh-huh, uh-huh ♪

34:33.000 --> 34:37.000
♪ Uh, uh, yeah,
yeah, yeah, yeah ♪

34:37.000 --> 34:39.000
♪ Yeah, huh, huh,
huh, uh-huh... ♪

34:39.000 --> 34:41.000
Lee-ah, right?

34:41.000 --> 34:43.000
It’s Leah.

34:43.000 --> 34:44.000
Oh, Leah, yeah.

34:44.000 --> 34:45.000
Well, I’m Emily.

34:45.000 --> 34:47.000
Everybody calls me Em.

34:47.000 --> 34:49.000
I was hoping you’d be back
before I finished cleaning.

34:49.000 --> 34:51.000
Here, let me help you.

34:51.000 --> 34:52.000
Oh. Jake didn’t
tell you about me?

34:52.000 --> 34:55.000
Uh, no... He did.

34:55.000 --> 34:58.000
He-he just didn’t mention
that you were coming today.

34:58.000 --> 35:01.000
I’m so sorry--
this place is a disaster.

35:01.000 --> 35:04.000
And I got to get this
stuff out of your way.

35:04.000 --> 35:05.000
Oh, it’s taken care of.

35:05.000 --> 35:08.000
Herbert, my husband, moved
everything into the back.

35:11.000 --> 35:13.000
Thank him for me.
(laughs)

35:13.000 --> 35:15.000
I will.

35:15.000 --> 35:17.000
Well, it looks like somebody’s
gonna be doing some baking.

35:17.000 --> 35:20.000
Yeah. I’m
making challas.

35:20.000 --> 35:23.000
The elderly lady I work for
on Wednesday, Mrs. Blaustein,

35:23.000 --> 35:25.000
she makes those, too.

35:25.000 --> 35:26.000
Maybe you know her.
No.

35:26.000 --> 35:30.000
Hm. I thought-- she wears
the same hair as you.

35:30.000 --> 35:33.000
Oh, because she’s married,
she wears a wig?

35:33.000 --> 35:34.000
Is that why?

35:34.000 --> 35:36.000
Our real hair

35:36.000 --> 35:38.000
shouldn’t excite men
other than our husbands.

35:38.000 --> 35:42.000
Mrs. Blaustein has
nothing to worry about
in that department.

35:42.000 --> 35:43.000
Mm-hmm.

35:43.000 --> 35:45.000
EMILY:
I’m guessing,

35:45.000 --> 35:48.000
but you being here

35:48.000 --> 35:50.000
has shaken things up a bit.

35:50.000 --> 35:51.000
What do you mean?

35:51.000 --> 35:55.000
You’re here,
and Carol isn’t.

35:55.000 --> 35:56.000
(Emily chuckling)
(laughs) No.

35:56.000 --> 35:58.000
No, it’s not like that.

35:58.000 --> 36:00.000
We’re roommates.

36:00.000 --> 36:03.000
Nothing more.

36:03.000 --> 36:05.000
Hm. Well, that’s too bad,

36:05.000 --> 36:07.000
because he is fine!

36:09.000 --> 36:11.000
How long have
you worked for Jake?
For years.

36:11.000 --> 36:13.000
But seriously,
he is a good man.

36:13.000 --> 36:15.000
Well...

36:15.000 --> 36:18.000
I’m hoping to get
to find out.

36:18.000 --> 36:20.000
He doesn’t spend
much time here.

36:20.000 --> 36:21.000
Oh, that’ll change.

36:21.000 --> 36:23.000
I have never known a man
to stay away from a home

36:23.000 --> 36:25.000
where there’s
someone cooking.

36:25.000 --> 36:27.000
Well, he doesn’t want
me cooking for him.

36:27.000 --> 36:29.000
That will definitely change.

36:36.000 --> 36:37.000
Carol, will you wait up?

36:37.000 --> 36:38.000
I don’t want to
speak to you.

36:38.000 --> 36:41.000
All right,
so don’t talk then.

36:41.000 --> 36:44.000
But please,
just take it.

36:44.000 --> 36:45.000
Hey, congratulations,

36:45.000 --> 36:47.000
you two, you finally did it.

36:47.000 --> 36:49.000
Let me know
where you’re registered.

37:16.000 --> 37:19.000
♪ ♪

37:47.000 --> 37:49.000
(whistle blows)

37:49.000 --> 37:50.000
(gasps)

37:50.000 --> 37:51.000
WOMAN:
Closing time.

37:51.000 --> 37:53.000
Almost 11:00.

37:53.000 --> 37:54.000
Five more minutes.

38:16.000 --> 38:19.000
♪ ♪

38:44.000 --> 38:47.000
I love it here
this time of day.

38:48.000 --> 38:50.000
I’m Gerry.

38:50.000 --> 38:51.000
Though some people here
call me Rabbi.

38:54.000 --> 38:56.000
It’s nice to meet you.

38:56.000 --> 38:57.000
I should go.

38:57.000 --> 39:01.000
I’d hate to think
that I’d sent you away.

39:01.000 --> 39:03.000
Well, you have a
beautiful shul.

39:03.000 --> 39:04.000
Thank you.

39:04.000 --> 39:06.000
I’m sorry, I’ve never
met a female rabbi.

39:06.000 --> 39:11.000
Wow, that’s a lot of pressure,
me being your first.

39:11.000 --> 39:13.000
So what brings you here?

39:13.000 --> 39:17.000
Oh, my brother-in-law’s got
an apartment in Georgetown.

39:17.000 --> 39:20.000
Well, technically
he’s my husband now,

39:20.000 --> 39:23.000
but really he’s just
my brother-in-law.

39:24.000 --> 39:27.000
The Levirate marriage?

39:27.000 --> 39:29.000
I thought that wasn’t
practiced any longer.

39:29.000 --> 39:31.000
It’s not.

39:31.000 --> 39:33.000
We were having the
Halizah ceremony,

39:33.000 --> 39:36.000
and... something happened.

39:37.000 --> 39:39.000
I was a part
of something

39:39.000 --> 39:42.000
being married
to Benjamin--

39:42.000 --> 39:45.000
having my family
around me, the shul.

39:45.000 --> 39:47.000
Yes.

39:47.000 --> 39:50.000
Now I’m trying to make
a life for myself.

39:50.000 --> 39:53.000
Jake has his life.

39:53.000 --> 39:55.000
But I’m having trouble
with all the alone time.

39:55.000 --> 39:57.000
(chuckles)

39:57.000 --> 39:58.000
That’s understandable.

39:58.000 --> 39:59.000
You miss your husband.

39:59.000 --> 40:02.000
I miss the job.

40:02.000 --> 40:06.000
I don’t have that
now... or a real home.

40:06.000 --> 40:09.000
I mean, it’s a place to
sleep, but it’s not a home.

40:09.000 --> 40:12.000
I really don’t know what
I thought would happen

40:12.000 --> 40:13.000
when I did this.

40:13.000 --> 40:15.000
This is the
first time

40:15.000 --> 40:18.000
I’ve ever run away,

40:18.000 --> 40:20.000
except for when I’d
sneak off to the movies.

40:20.000 --> 40:21.000
Sometimes on Sundays,

40:21.000 --> 40:25.000
I run away
and I go bowling.

40:25.000 --> 40:26.000
Shh.

40:26.000 --> 40:28.000
(laughs)

40:31.000 --> 40:33.000
This will get easier, Leah.

40:33.000 --> 40:35.000
Life will take hold again.

40:35.000 --> 40:38.000
Looks to me like you need
a little smothering.

40:38.000 --> 40:40.000
In a good way.

40:45.000 --> 40:48.000
Hey, thanks for coming.

40:48.000 --> 40:52.000
It looks really pretty on you.

40:52.000 --> 40:54.000
Thank you, it’s stunning.

40:54.000 --> 40:55.000
Must have really set you back.

40:58.000 --> 40:59.000
Miss?
Yes?

40:59.000 --> 41:00.000
Grilled salmon to go.

41:00.000 --> 41:03.000
Mm-hmm.

41:03.000 --> 41:05.000
And for you?

41:05.000 --> 41:08.000
Hamburger,
medium rare, for here,

41:08.000 --> 41:10.000
and a Coke, thanks.

41:10.000 --> 41:12.000
Okay.

41:14.000 --> 41:16.000
So what happened
to having lunch?

41:16.000 --> 41:20.000
Look, I’ve been trying to
wrap my brain around this.

41:20.000 --> 41:22.000
I understand
why you did it.

41:22.000 --> 41:25.000
You just have to end it if
you want us to be together.

41:25.000 --> 41:27.000
I just can’t do
it any other way.

41:29.000 --> 41:32.000
Okay.

41:32.000 --> 41:34.000
I’ll talk to Leah
this weekend.

41:34.000 --> 41:35.000
(sighs)

41:35.000 --> 41:36.000
Good.

41:36.000 --> 41:37.000
I’ll stay.

41:37.000 --> 41:39.000
Great.

41:42.000 --> 41:44.000
(door opens
and closes)

41:44.000 --> 41:46.000
JAKE:
Leah?

41:49.000 --> 41:52.000
Leah?

41:52.000 --> 41:54.000
(knocking)

42:24.000 --> 42:27.000
♪ ♪

42:34.000 --> 42:38.000
(both speaking Hebrew)

42:40.000 --> 42:42.000
BOTH:
Amen.

42:42.000 --> 42:44.000
ALL:
Amen.

42:55.000 --> 42:56.000
Shabbat Shalom.

42:56.000 --> 42:58.000
Shabbat Shalom.

42:58.000 --> 43:02.000
ALL:
Shabbat Shalom.

43:02.000 --> 43:03.000
MAN:
Nice service.

43:10.000 --> 43:12.000
Shabbat Shalom.

43:12.000 --> 43:14.000
Good Shabbos.

43:14.000 --> 43:15.000
She’s been here for a month.

43:15.000 --> 43:16.000
Maybe she’s out with friends.

43:16.000 --> 43:17.000
JAKE:
Leah has no friends.

43:17.000 --> 43:19.000
Look, I got some takeout.

43:19.000 --> 43:21.000
Come over, and when you
get back, she’ll be there.

43:21.000 --> 43:23.000
It always works that way.

43:23.000 --> 43:25.000
Yeah, you’re probably right.

43:25.000 --> 43:27.000
All right,
I’ll be there in a few minutes.

43:27.000 --> 43:30.000
Bye.

43:30.000 --> 43:33.000
(sighs)

43:39.000 --> 43:41.000
Go ahead, Jake.

43:41.000 --> 43:42.000
What?

43:42.000 --> 43:43.000
Call her.

43:43.000 --> 43:46.000
You know you want to.

43:46.000 --> 43:47.000
Just one more time.

43:51.000 --> 43:53.000
Maybe she met someone.

43:53.000 --> 43:55.000
Leah is not like that.

43:56.000 --> 43:58.000
You have feelings for her.

43:58.000 --> 44:00.000
(scoffs)

44:00.000 --> 44:02.000
Don’t be silly.

44:02.000 --> 44:04.000
I can’t believe this.

44:04.000 --> 44:06.000
I’ve become the other woman.

44:06.000 --> 44:08.000
What are you talking about?

44:08.000 --> 44:10.000
You’re making me out
to be the bad guy

44:10.000 --> 44:12.000
and I’ve done nothing
to deserve this.

44:14.000 --> 44:18.000
You’re right.

44:18.000 --> 44:22.000
I’m sorry.

44:22.000 --> 44:24.000
Look.

44:24.000 --> 44:29.000
You and me,
Jamaica, my treat.

44:29.000 --> 44:30.000
What do you say?

44:30.000 --> 44:32.000
A nice long
weekend.

44:32.000 --> 44:35.000
As soon as Leah is gone,
once, once she’s found.

44:37.000 --> 44:39.000
Yes?

44:39.000 --> 44:40.000
Hmm?

44:40.000 --> 44:42.000
No?

44:42.000 --> 44:44.000
Hmm?

44:44.000 --> 44:47.000
Is that a yes?

44:47.000 --> 44:49.000
WOMAN (over intercom):
Dr. Perkins,
call the pharmacy, please.

44:49.000 --> 44:50.000
Dr. Perkins,
please call the pharmacy.

44:50.000 --> 44:52.000
Hey.

44:52.000 --> 44:54.000
Hey, man,
what’s up?

44:54.000 --> 44:56.000
None.

44:56.000 --> 44:58.000
Called the
police?

44:58.000 --> 45:02.000
48 hours before I can report
a missing person.

45:02.000 --> 45:04.000
Called the morgue.

45:04.000 --> 45:06.000
Thankfully nothing.

45:13.000 --> 45:16.000
(door unlocking)

45:16.000 --> 45:18.000
(door opens)

45:21.000 --> 45:23.000
(sighs)

45:23.000 --> 45:25.000
Where have you been?

45:25.000 --> 45:28.000
I’ve been going out of my
mind worrying about you.

45:28.000 --> 45:30.000
Y-You didn’t answer my calls,
you didn’t leave a note.

45:30.000 --> 45:32.000
You can’t do that, Leah.

45:32.000 --> 45:35.000
I spent Shabbos
with the rabbi.

45:37.000 --> 45:39.000
I don’t use the phone
on Shabbos.

45:39.000 --> 45:43.000
Shabbos... of course.

45:43.000 --> 45:44.000
(sighs)

45:44.000 --> 45:48.000
Look, you need to tell me
when you go out.

45:48.000 --> 45:50.000
I don’t need to tell you, the
same way that you don’t tell me.

45:50.000 --> 45:51.000
This isn’t
Brooklyn.

45:51.000 --> 45:53.000
I’m responsible for you.

45:56.000 --> 45:59.000
No one told you to do that,
so stop.

45:59.000 --> 46:00.000
(scoffs)

46:00.000 --> 46:02.000
Fine.

46:02.000 --> 46:04.000
Good.

46:15.000 --> 46:17.000
(unzips and zips purse)

46:22.000 --> 46:25.000
I’m sorry.

46:25.000 --> 46:27.000
I was looking
for an address book,

46:27.000 --> 46:29.000
some, some way to find you.

46:32.000 --> 46:35.000
I like what you’ve done

46:35.000 --> 46:38.000
with the room.

46:38.000 --> 46:41.000
(sighs)

46:41.000 --> 46:43.000
You look good with long hair.

46:44.000 --> 46:47.000
The picture
on the desk.

46:50.000 --> 46:52.000
Thank you.

46:52.000 --> 46:54.000
I thought
maybe you packed up and left.

46:59.000 --> 47:02.000
Is that what you were hoping?

47:02.000 --> 47:04.000
No.

47:04.000 --> 47:06.000
No, I wasn’t.

47:09.000 --> 47:11.000
I asked you to come here,

47:11.000 --> 47:13.000
but I’m not sure I
know how to do this.

47:13.000 --> 47:14.000
Let’s stop then.

47:14.000 --> 47:17.000
This... is ridiculous.

47:17.000 --> 47:19.000
I don’t want to feel
like a boarder,

47:19.000 --> 47:21.000
and you, you don’t even
treat me like I’m a guest.

47:21.000 --> 47:23.000
When I cook
for you,

47:23.000 --> 47:25.000
you’re never home to eat it.
I told you not to.

47:25.000 --> 47:27.000
I can’t help it.
I like to cook.

47:27.000 --> 47:28.000
And you’re a great cook.

47:28.000 --> 47:29.000
How would you know?

47:29.000 --> 47:32.000
I liked your eggs.

47:36.000 --> 47:38.000
(sighs)

47:38.000 --> 47:40.000
(laughs)

47:41.000 --> 47:44.000
(chuckles)

47:44.000 --> 47:46.000
Do you like Chinese food?

47:48.000 --> 47:51.000
This is my first time
asking a man out.

47:51.000 --> 47:55.000
So... you never just
hung out with guys?

47:55.000 --> 47:58.000
Where I’m from, we don’t go
out with the opposite sex

47:58.000 --> 48:01.000
besides our husbands
or our brothers.

48:01.000 --> 48:03.000
Even in high school?

48:03.000 --> 48:06.000
No, we’re kept separate until
we’re ready to get married,

48:06.000 --> 48:08.000
and then we’re set up
by a family friend

48:08.000 --> 48:11.000
or a professional
matchmaker.

48:11.000 --> 48:13.000
You mean
like you and my brother?

48:13.000 --> 48:16.000
Yes.

48:16.000 --> 48:18.000
Esther’s husband
set us up.

48:18.000 --> 48:19.000
Then you guys dated.
It’s not

48:19.000 --> 48:22.000
like what you would
consider dating--

48:22.000 --> 48:24.000
dinner, dancing.

48:24.000 --> 48:26.000
(chuckles)

48:28.000 --> 48:31.000
It’s more like seeing if we
could make a life together.

48:31.000 --> 48:33.000
Excuse me,
may I?

48:33.000 --> 48:35.000
Thank you.

48:35.000 --> 48:37.000
Thanks.

48:37.000 --> 48:40.000
So how did you
meet Carol?

48:40.000 --> 48:42.000
At the hospital.

48:42.000 --> 48:43.000
We had the same
late lunch schedule,

48:43.000 --> 48:44.000
started eating together,

48:44.000 --> 48:49.000
and, and it turned
into what we have now.

48:49.000 --> 48:52.000
She can’t be too pleased
with this arrangement.

48:52.000 --> 48:53.000
(chuckles)

48:55.000 --> 48:58.000
I should move out.

48:58.000 --> 49:00.000
It would be
easier for you.

49:06.000 --> 49:08.000
Look, you’re the one
who uprooted your life

49:08.000 --> 49:11.000
because I asked you to.

49:11.000 --> 49:14.000
When you’re ready,
I’ll help you find a place.

49:14.000 --> 49:18.000
Till then, let’s just keep
this arrangement.

49:18.000 --> 49:20.000
From now on, we’re gonna
let the other one know

49:20.000 --> 49:22.000
when we plan
to spend the night out.

49:22.000 --> 49:23.000
Deal?

49:24.000 --> 49:26.000
Deal.

49:30.000 --> 49:32.000
Are you cold?

49:32.000 --> 49:33.000
Oh.
Here.

49:33.000 --> 49:34.000
Thank you.

49:34.000 --> 49:36.000
Sure.

49:38.000 --> 49:40.000
Here you go.

49:43.000 --> 49:45.000
You’re not at all
what I expected.

49:45.000 --> 49:48.000
Why, what did
you expect?

49:48.000 --> 49:50.000
I don’t know.

49:50.000 --> 49:51.000
You’re kind of sassy.

49:51.000 --> 49:55.000
"You got spunk, kid."

49:55.000 --> 49:59.000
Bogart.

49:59.000 --> 50:03.000
Seriously, though,
Ben was smart to grab you.

50:03.000 --> 50:07.000
He was a lucky guy.

50:07.000 --> 50:09.000
Thank you.

50:13.000 --> 50:17.000
You know...

50:17.000 --> 50:19.000
the day he died
I told everyone

50:19.000 --> 50:23.000
I was on Delancey Street
looking for Torah covers...

50:23.000 --> 50:27.000
(quavering):
...but really I was
at a revival house

50:27.000 --> 50:29.000
watching The
Way We Were.

50:32.000 --> 50:36.000
So Ben couldn’t find me
to say good-bye.

50:36.000 --> 50:39.000
(phone ringing)

50:43.000 --> 50:45.000
Hey.

50:45.000 --> 50:46.000
Yeah, she’s found.

50:46.000 --> 50:49.000
Shabbos.

50:49.000 --> 50:52.000
Yeah.

50:52.000 --> 50:54.000
I’ll be there
in 30 minutes.

50:54.000 --> 50:56.000
Okay.

50:56.000 --> 50:57.000
All right, bye.

50:57.000 --> 51:00.000
Sorry.

51:00.000 --> 51:02.000
It’s okay.

51:02.000 --> 51:05.000
(vehicle starts)

51:06.000 --> 51:08.000
(drives away)

51:38.000 --> 51:41.000
♪ ♪

51:56.000 --> 51:58.000
(sighs)

52:32.000 --> 52:34.000
Want some help?

52:37.000 --> 52:39.000
Sure.

52:41.000 --> 52:43.000
Here, you want
to translate?

52:47.000 --> 52:49.000
"On Tuesday, Kate
buys an apple pie.

52:49.000 --> 52:51.000
"She eats two-fifths
of the pie that night.

52:51.000 --> 52:53.000
"On Thursday, she
takes out the pie again

52:53.000 --> 52:55.000
and eats two-fifths
of what is left."

52:55.000 --> 52:56.000
You see what I mean?

52:56.000 --> 52:58.000
What’s the lowest
common denominator?

52:58.000 --> 53:02.000
So five...
five times five is 25.

53:02.000 --> 53:03.000
Remember, two-fifths
of what’s left.

53:03.000 --> 53:08.000
So... so it’s 9/25.

53:08.000 --> 53:09.000
So the answer is "D"?

53:09.000 --> 53:11.000
You know this, you’re
just over-studied.

53:11.000 --> 53:12.000
(sighs)

53:14.000 --> 53:17.000
You know what I do
when I feel burnt out?
What?

53:34.000 --> 53:37.000
I told you
I don’t really know how to swim.

53:37.000 --> 53:38.000
I’ll teach you.

53:49.000 --> 53:51.000
You planning

53:51.000 --> 53:53.000
on swimming in your towel?

54:23.000 --> 54:26.000
♪ ♪

54:47.000 --> 54:49.000
(beeping)

54:53.000 --> 54:55.000
JAKE:
Hey, Leah, I forgot to tell you

54:55.000 --> 54:58.000
that Carol and I are leaving
Wednesday for Jamaica.

54:58.000 --> 55:01.000
I’ll be back Sunday,
but we’ll talk before then.

55:03.000 --> 55:05.000
Herbert loves
those scary movies.

55:05.000 --> 55:07.000
You know,
any excuse to grab for me.

55:07.000 --> 55:09.000
Though I did make him
pick me up that one movie--

55:09.000 --> 55:13.000
you know, the one you told me
about-- Doctor Zhivago.

55:13.000 --> 55:14.000
Leah?

55:20.000 --> 55:22.000
I’m in love with him, Em.

55:22.000 --> 55:25.000
Oh.

55:25.000 --> 55:27.000
Well, have you two,
you know...?

55:27.000 --> 55:29.000
No.

55:29.000 --> 55:30.000
Of course not.

55:30.000 --> 55:34.000
Jake loves Carol.

55:34.000 --> 55:36.000
How could I have let
this happen?

55:36.000 --> 55:39.000
He’s taking her to Jamaica.

55:39.000 --> 55:41.000
Well, maybe to try
to convince himself

55:41.000 --> 55:43.000
there’s nothing
between you and him.

55:43.000 --> 55:44.000
Oh,

55:44.000 --> 55:46.000
honey.

55:46.000 --> 55:48.000
You are not the type of person

55:48.000 --> 55:49.000
to have these feelings
for no reason.

55:49.000 --> 55:50.000
Obviously,

55:50.000 --> 55:54.000
I am.

55:54.000 --> 55:58.000
He was just being nice.

55:58.000 --> 56:03.000
Here, men can be nice
and take you to dinner...

56:03.000 --> 56:05.000
(quavering):
...and swimming,
and it doesn’t mean anything.

56:05.000 --> 56:06.000
I’ve got to move out, Em.

56:06.000 --> 56:08.000
Leah.

56:11.000 --> 56:13.000
(horns honking)

56:16.000 --> 56:18.000
Hi, I’m calling
about the studio apartment.

56:18.000 --> 56:20.000
Is that still available?

56:21.000 --> 56:24.000
Yeah, that would be great.

56:24.000 --> 56:25.000
Oh.

56:28.000 --> 56:30.000
Could you hold on?

56:32.000 --> 56:34.000
Hi, Mama.

56:34.000 --> 56:36.000
No, I’m shopping for dinner.

56:37.000 --> 56:38.000
I think this arrhythmia case is

56:38.000 --> 56:39.000
a better choice
for Journal Club.

56:39.000 --> 56:41.000
Dr. Lever,

56:41.000 --> 56:42.000
your wife is
on the phone.

56:42.000 --> 56:43.000
My what?
Your wife.

56:43.000 --> 56:45.000
JAKE:
Leah?

56:45.000 --> 56:47.000
My mother is coming here.

56:47.000 --> 56:48.000
When?

56:48.000 --> 56:50.000
Tomorrow.
Tomorrow?

56:50.000 --> 56:52.000
Yes.

56:52.000 --> 56:55.000
She’s coming to check on us...
and this marriage.

56:55.000 --> 56:59.000
Uh... I have got to make
your place look like a home.

56:59.000 --> 57:00.000
Leah, why don’t you
just tell her?

57:00.000 --> 57:03.000
No, n--
you don’t "just tell" Mama.

57:03.000 --> 57:05.000
Well, this might be the perfect
time to stand up to her.

57:05.000 --> 57:07.000
Just tell her the truth
about us.

57:07.000 --> 57:08.000
You don’t understand.

57:08.000 --> 57:09.000
She will make my life
a living hell.

57:09.000 --> 57:11.000
She can do that.

57:11.000 --> 57:13.000
She’s a professional.

57:13.000 --> 57:15.000
Look, I know you’re going away,

57:15.000 --> 57:17.000
and I can just make something up
about why you’re not there,

57:17.000 --> 57:19.000
but...

57:19.000 --> 57:24.000
if you’d help me to get
your apartment into shape,

57:24.000 --> 57:26.000
I promise I’ll never ask
anything of you ever again.

57:27.000 --> 57:30.000
Well?

57:33.000 --> 57:35.000
BOTH:
We’ll take it.

57:35.000 --> 57:37.000
Excellent.

57:37.000 --> 57:38.000
What else?

57:38.000 --> 57:40.000
Um, curtains.

57:40.000 --> 57:42.000
end tables,
lamps.

57:42.000 --> 57:43.000
Let me see.

57:43.000 --> 57:45.000
Let’s get a rug
for the coffee table.

57:45.000 --> 57:47.000
I’ve got
some fantastic area rugs,

57:47.000 --> 57:49.000
20% off.

57:50.000 --> 57:52.000
Those pillows are perfect.

57:55.000 --> 57:57.000
Right up her alley.

58:00.000 --> 58:04.000
Which medical conference
should I say you’re attending?

58:04.000 --> 58:08.000
Let me look at the schedule
to see what’s coming up.

58:17.000 --> 58:18.000
Hi.

58:18.000 --> 58:20.000
How did you
like the...?

58:22.000 --> 58:24.000
(Jake clears throat)

58:24.000 --> 58:26.000
Um, we’re looking

58:26.000 --> 58:28.000
for very simple wedding bands
like those.

58:31.000 --> 58:33.000
What are you going
to make your mom for dinner?

58:33.000 --> 58:36.000
Um, brisket.

58:36.000 --> 58:38.000
I do love
your brisket.

58:45.000 --> 58:47.000
What?

58:49.000 --> 58:50.000
(chuckles)

58:50.000 --> 58:52.000
You’re not going
to believe this.

58:52.000 --> 58:54.000
It involves Leah.

58:54.000 --> 58:57.000
Her mother--
she’s coming.

58:57.000 --> 58:58.000
I have to help her.

58:58.000 --> 59:00.000
I’m sorry,
but I have to.

59:00.000 --> 59:05.000
I-I will more than
make this up to you--

59:05.000 --> 59:06.000
I will do the re-booking.

59:06.000 --> 59:08.000
Whenever you say--
next week

59:08.000 --> 59:09.000
if that works for you.

59:09.000 --> 59:11.000
Really, no more interferences.

59:11.000 --> 59:14.000
You told me that she was going
to get her own place

59:14.000 --> 59:15.000
and you were end this marriage.

59:15.000 --> 59:17.000
I know.

59:17.000 --> 59:19.000
But I felt like a jerk.

59:19.000 --> 59:20.000
I mean, she came
down here for me.

59:20.000 --> 59:23.000
I just can’t abandon her.

59:23.000 --> 59:25.000
Good-bye, Jake.

59:25.000 --> 59:29.000
(over P.A.):
Dr. Lao, pick up
extension 632.

59:29.000 --> 59:32.000
Dr. Lao, pick up extension 632.

59:32.000 --> 59:35.000
LEAH:
Thank you for coming with me.
Yeah, of course.

59:35.000 --> 59:36.000
Oh, when you get
to Jamaica

59:36.000 --> 59:37.000
don’t forget to call

59:37.000 --> 59:39.000
to make it look like
you’re checking in.

59:39.000 --> 59:41.000
Well, actually, there’s
been a change in plans.

59:41.000 --> 59:42.000
I’m staying.

59:42.000 --> 59:45.000
Really?

59:45.000 --> 59:47.000
Vayzmeer!

59:47.000 --> 59:48.000
What?

59:48.000 --> 59:50.000
If you’re staying,

59:50.000 --> 59:53.000
that means I’ll be sleeping in
your bedroom with you in it.

59:55.000 --> 59:57.000
Oh, yeah, that’s right.

59:58.000 --> 59:59.000
Leah.

01:00:04.000 --> 01:00:06.000
Hi, Mama.

01:00:07.000 --> 01:00:08.000
Oh...

01:00:11.000 --> 01:00:12.000
Hi, Mom.

01:00:12.000 --> 01:00:13.000
Could you
get this?
Sure.

01:00:13.000 --> 01:00:15.000
Uh... I’ll take that.
Thank you.

01:00:15.000 --> 01:00:16.000
How was your trip?

01:00:16.000 --> 01:00:18.000
Short.

01:00:18.000 --> 01:00:19.000
Like your skirt.

01:00:29.000 --> 01:00:31.000
Oh.

01:00:36.000 --> 01:00:38.000
Uh-huh.

01:00:42.000 --> 01:00:44.000
Ah.

01:00:44.000 --> 01:00:46.000
Nice pillows.

01:00:50.000 --> 01:00:51.000
No.

01:00:51.000 --> 01:00:53.000
Honey...

01:00:53.000 --> 01:00:54.000
we’re having brisket tonight.

01:00:54.000 --> 01:00:56.000
No butter.

01:00:56.000 --> 01:00:57.000
Oh! Of course.

01:00:57.000 --> 01:00:59.000
I’m sorry, sweetcakes.

01:00:59.000 --> 01:01:00.000
"Sweetcakes"?

01:01:00.000 --> 01:01:03.000
It’s... his name for me, Mama.

01:01:03.000 --> 01:01:07.000
(quietly):
Well, I certainly hope
he doesn’t use it in public.

01:01:10.000 --> 01:01:11.000
It smells delicious.

01:01:16.000 --> 01:01:18.000
Mama,

01:01:18.000 --> 01:01:20.000
Jake is one of three
who was accepted

01:01:20.000 --> 01:01:22.000
to the cardiac
fellowship program.

01:01:22.000 --> 01:01:24.000
Out of thousands.

01:01:24.000 --> 01:01:26.000
Actually, it was hundreds.

01:01:29.000 --> 01:01:31.000
Do you belong to a shul, Jake?

01:01:31.000 --> 01:01:33.000
(clears throat quietly)

01:01:33.000 --> 01:01:34.000
A shul?
Yeah.

01:01:34.000 --> 01:01:36.000
No.

01:01:36.000 --> 01:01:38.000
I belong to a gym.

01:01:38.000 --> 01:01:39.000
(chuckles softly)

01:01:42.000 --> 01:01:46.000
That’s the sense of humor
you said he had.

01:01:46.000 --> 01:01:48.000
JAKE:
I got Leah there

01:01:48.000 --> 01:01:50.000
for a swimming lesson.

01:01:50.000 --> 01:01:52.000
Hm.

01:01:54.000 --> 01:01:58.000
Time for recreation;
no time for shul.

01:01:58.000 --> 01:02:00.000
JAKE:
We talked...

01:02:00.000 --> 01:02:01.000
about joining,

01:02:01.000 --> 01:02:03.000
for the future.

01:02:03.000 --> 01:02:05.000
Does the future
include a family?

01:02:05.000 --> 01:02:08.000
Sure, yes.

01:02:08.000 --> 01:02:09.000
After I get
my practice started.

01:02:09.000 --> 01:02:11.000
I want to be the kind of dad

01:02:11.000 --> 01:02:12.000
who has time to spend
with his kids.

01:02:12.000 --> 01:02:14.000
Then what’s Leah’s job?

01:02:16.000 --> 01:02:18.000
Oh. Well...

01:02:18.000 --> 01:02:19.000
my wife.

01:02:21.000 --> 01:02:23.000
Leah’s...

01:02:23.000 --> 01:02:24.000
gonna make
a great mom.

01:02:24.000 --> 01:02:26.000
Just as you have.

01:02:26.000 --> 01:02:28.000
And wha-what a cook.

01:02:28.000 --> 01:02:30.000
But you’re still the best, Mama.

01:02:30.000 --> 01:02:31.000
Yes, you are.

01:02:31.000 --> 01:02:34.000
Are you saying
I’m better than your wife?

01:02:35.000 --> 01:02:37.000
(clears throat):
Uh...

01:02:43.000 --> 01:02:45.000
I-I don’t have an answer
for that one.

01:02:47.000 --> 01:02:50.000
(basketball game playing on TV)

01:02:50.000 --> 01:02:53.000
(TV turns off)

01:02:53.000 --> 01:02:54.000
I’d say we pulled it off.

01:02:54.000 --> 01:02:56.000
(laughs) Shh.

01:02:56.000 --> 01:02:58.000
(big sigh)

01:02:58.000 --> 01:03:00.000
That’s just a warm-up.

01:03:00.000 --> 01:03:02.000
Wait till tomorrow.

01:03:02.000 --> 01:03:06.000
(sighs) When you brought up
the swimming...

01:03:06.000 --> 01:03:07.000
What, you’re not allowed
to swim?

01:03:07.000 --> 01:03:09.000
Not with the opposite sex.

01:03:09.000 --> 01:03:12.000
Where’s the fun in that?

01:03:19.000 --> 01:03:23.000
Do you have an extra blanket?

01:03:23.000 --> 01:03:26.000
Yeah, it’s in the closet--
I’ll get it.
I’ll get it, I’ll get it.

01:03:31.000 --> 01:03:32.000
(loud clattering)

01:03:34.000 --> 01:03:36.000
Shh-shh...

01:03:40.000 --> 01:03:42.000
Sorry.

01:03:42.000 --> 01:03:44.000
Here.

01:03:45.000 --> 01:03:47.000
(groans)
(gasps)

01:03:47.000 --> 01:03:48.000
What?

01:03:48.000 --> 01:03:50.000
I left my nightgown
under the pillow.

01:03:51.000 --> 01:03:53.000
Oh, no.

01:03:53.000 --> 01:03:56.000
What do we do?

01:03:56.000 --> 01:03:58.000
I’ll just tell her that

01:03:58.000 --> 01:04:00.000
I had to sleep
in the guest room,

01:04:00.000 --> 01:04:02.000
’cause you, uh, had
the German measles.

01:04:02.000 --> 01:04:04.000
(laughs)

01:04:04.000 --> 01:04:07.000
Look, if she asks,
go with a cold.

01:04:07.000 --> 01:04:10.000
Or even better, say
your snoring kept me up,
and I had an early call.

01:04:10.000 --> 01:04:12.000
That’s good.

01:04:12.000 --> 01:04:14.000
I don’t know if I snore.

01:04:14.000 --> 01:04:16.000
Look, don’t worry,
we’ll figure it out.

01:04:16.000 --> 01:04:17.000
Okay.

01:04:23.000 --> 01:04:25.000
Here, try these.

01:04:25.000 --> 01:04:27.000
Oh.

01:04:27.000 --> 01:04:28.000
Thanks.

01:04:46.000 --> 01:04:47.000
MAN (on TV):
Find romance.

01:04:47.000 --> 01:04:50.000
Jamaica awaits.

01:04:50.000 --> 01:04:51.000
Come find your paradise.

01:04:51.000 --> 01:04:53.000
Jamaica.

01:04:53.000 --> 01:04:55.000
(tropical music plays)

01:05:27.000 --> 01:05:28.000
(exhales)

01:05:31.000 --> 01:05:33.000
(laughs quietly)

01:05:33.000 --> 01:05:34.000
Leah, the bed is

01:05:34.000 --> 01:05:37.000
wider than Rhode Island.

01:05:40.000 --> 01:05:41.000
Look.

01:05:43.000 --> 01:05:44.000
I’m in Massachusetts.

01:05:53.000 --> 01:05:54.000
I’m sorry.

01:05:54.000 --> 01:05:56.000
Um...

01:05:56.000 --> 01:06:00.000
I can see how this is all
really new for you.

01:06:01.000 --> 01:06:04.000
You do whatever
makes you feel comfortable.

01:06:35.000 --> 01:06:38.000
I’m gonna turn
the light off now.

01:06:39.000 --> 01:06:40.000
Ready?

01:06:51.000 --> 01:06:55.000
This is like that movie,
It Happened One Night.

01:06:55.000 --> 01:06:56.000
I don’t know that one.

01:06:56.000 --> 01:07:00.000
Black-and-white, 1934.

01:07:00.000 --> 01:07:02.000
Clark Gable
and Claudette Colbert.

01:07:02.000 --> 01:07:06.000
They shared a room,
not married, in a motel,

01:07:06.000 --> 01:07:09.000
and they were broke,
so Clark Gable hung a sheet

01:07:09.000 --> 01:07:12.000
between their beds.

01:07:12.000 --> 01:07:14.000
Called it
the "Wall of Jericho."

01:07:14.000 --> 01:07:18.000
Was she worried
that he’d try something?

01:07:18.000 --> 01:07:20.000
Or was he worried
that she’d try something?

01:07:24.000 --> 01:07:27.000
I don’t know.

01:07:29.000 --> 01:07:31.000
Good night.

01:07:33.000 --> 01:07:35.000
Good night, Leah.

01:07:35.000 --> 01:07:37.000
♪ ♪

01:07:45.000 --> 01:07:47.000
This would be the perfect
school for me, Mama.

01:07:47.000 --> 01:07:49.000
If I can get in.

01:07:49.000 --> 01:07:51.000
It’s close to
the apartment.

01:07:51.000 --> 01:07:55.000
I am already familiar
with the library.

01:07:55.000 --> 01:07:56.000
And thankfully,
you don’t have to choose

01:07:56.000 --> 01:07:57.000
a major until
sophomore year.

01:07:57.000 --> 01:08:01.000
Which isn’t gonna be anything
that involves math.

01:08:01.000 --> 01:08:02.000
The shul is right up here.

01:08:09.000 --> 01:08:11.000
Uh, this is far enough.

01:08:11.000 --> 01:08:12.000
No, Mama,

01:08:12.000 --> 01:08:14.000
I want to show you.
What? What?

01:08:14.000 --> 01:08:16.000
Another one of your charades?

01:08:16.000 --> 01:08:18.000
I found your nightgown.

01:08:20.000 --> 01:08:21.000
And don’t tell me
you slept there

01:08:21.000 --> 01:08:24.000
because you got sick
or Jake did.

01:08:24.000 --> 01:08:27.000
And now you want to bring me
to a reformed temple

01:08:27.000 --> 01:08:29.000
with a woman rabbi,
and you think

01:08:29.000 --> 01:08:30.000
this is okay?

01:08:30.000 --> 01:08:32.000
Leah,

01:08:32.000 --> 01:08:34.000
you come from two
completely different worlds.

01:08:34.000 --> 01:08:35.000
You are not right

01:08:35.000 --> 01:08:37.000
for each other.
You don’t know him.

01:08:37.000 --> 01:08:38.000
No, I but I know you!

01:08:38.000 --> 01:08:42.000
You don’t hold
the same values as him.

01:08:42.000 --> 01:08:44.000
Where is his love of God, huh?

01:08:44.000 --> 01:08:46.000
He jokes.

01:08:46.000 --> 01:08:50.000
He puts vanity...
he puts a gym before God.

01:08:50.000 --> 01:08:52.000
Well, he was nervous;
you scare him.

01:08:52.000 --> 01:08:55.000
He puts his career before God?

01:08:55.000 --> 01:08:56.000
He’s ambitious.

01:08:56.000 --> 01:08:58.000
And his profession
is saving lives.

01:09:00.000 --> 01:09:01.000
You’re in love with him?

01:09:04.000 --> 01:09:07.000
God and you come last
in this man’s life.

01:09:07.000 --> 01:09:09.000
It’s all about him!

01:09:11.000 --> 01:09:13.000
You’re not being fair.

01:09:13.000 --> 01:09:16.000
I am telling you,

01:09:16.000 --> 01:09:19.000
this is wrong.

01:09:19.000 --> 01:09:22.000
You’re becoming so assimilated
that God won’t know who you are.

01:09:22.000 --> 01:09:24.000
I can’t find you.

01:09:25.000 --> 01:09:27.000
It’s still me.

01:09:27.000 --> 01:09:29.000
I’m still observant.

01:09:29.000 --> 01:09:32.000
Okay, so...

01:09:32.000 --> 01:09:35.000
come back with me today,

01:09:35.000 --> 01:09:37.000
and we’ll tell
everybody at home...

01:09:37.000 --> 01:09:39.000
Mama, this is home!

01:09:44.000 --> 01:09:46.000
♪ ♪

01:09:58.000 --> 01:10:01.000
Know that you have a home
back in Brooklyn.

01:10:22.000 --> 01:10:24.000
Hey. Sorry I’m late.

01:10:24.000 --> 01:10:27.000
Shlomo’s was a madhouse.

01:10:27.000 --> 01:10:29.000
So, is it a good thing
or a bad thing

01:10:29.000 --> 01:10:30.000
that your mom left early?

01:10:30.000 --> 01:10:33.000
(sighs)
Did she say
something

01:10:33.000 --> 01:10:34.000
to upset you?

01:10:35.000 --> 01:10:38.000
I moved my clothes
out of your room.

01:10:38.000 --> 01:10:42.000
We can return the furniture,
bring back your pool table.

01:10:42.000 --> 01:10:44.000
Thanks, but I kind of like
what we’ve done here.

01:10:51.000 --> 01:10:53.000
You want chopsticks or fork?

01:10:53.000 --> 01:10:55.000
Chopsticks are good.

01:11:01.000 --> 01:11:05.000
So, when are you and Carol
leaving on your trip?

01:11:12.000 --> 01:11:14.000
We’re not.

01:11:14.000 --> 01:11:17.000
There is no more
Carol and me.

01:11:17.000 --> 01:11:19.000
We broke up.

01:11:19.000 --> 01:11:21.000
It’s my fault.

01:11:21.000 --> 01:11:23.000
You canceled your
trip to help me.

01:11:23.000 --> 01:11:26.000
No, it is not
your fault at all.

01:11:26.000 --> 01:11:29.000
The truth is, I was
never gonna marry Carol.

01:11:29.000 --> 01:11:31.000
And I...

01:11:31.000 --> 01:11:34.000
I probably should’ve told
her that a long time ago.

01:11:34.000 --> 01:11:36.000
I guess I just
got comfortable.

01:11:38.000 --> 01:11:40.000
(laughs)
Besides, she’s a...

01:11:40.000 --> 01:11:43.000
she was a better
dancer than me.

01:11:45.000 --> 01:11:49.000
It’s a black-tie event
for a doctor who’s retiring.

01:11:49.000 --> 01:11:51.000
I want you to go with me.

01:11:51.000 --> 01:11:53.000
I’d like you to go with me.

01:11:56.000 --> 01:11:59.000
(laughs)
Will you go with me?

01:11:59.000 --> 01:12:02.000
Is this a date?

01:12:02.000 --> 01:12:04.000
Yeah, it’s a date.

01:12:04.000 --> 01:12:06.000
(laughs)

01:12:06.000 --> 01:12:11.000
EMILY:
We don’t want you trashy,
stuff all hanging out.

01:12:11.000 --> 01:12:12.000
Everybody seeing what you had
for breakfast.

01:12:12.000 --> 01:12:15.000
We need you looking clean.

01:12:15.000 --> 01:12:17.000
All right, try those.

01:12:17.000 --> 01:12:19.000
See what else
we got here.

01:12:19.000 --> 01:12:23.000
Ooh! Ooh-ooh-ooh, yes.
Like it.

01:12:23.000 --> 01:12:26.000
All right, go.
Put it on. Hurry up.

01:12:55.000 --> 01:12:58.000
♪ ♪

